dreisoft.tresos.tresosdb.api.model.v1.swcomponenttemplate.endtoendprotection

Interface IEndToEndDescription

  • All Superinterfaces:
    IEntity

    public interface IEndToEndDescription
extends IEntity
    IEndToEndDescription: Entity class of the tresosDB model.

    This meta-class contains information about end-to-end protection. The set of applicable attributes depends on the actual value of the category attribute of EndToEndProtection.

      • getCounterOffset

        long getCounterOffset()
        Query the value of the attribute CounterOffset.

        Bit offset of Counter from the beginning of the Array representation of the Signal Group/DataElementPrototype (MSB order, bit numbering: bit 0 is the least important). The offset shall be a multiplicity of 4 and it should be 8 whenever possible. For example, offset 8 means that the counter will take the low nibble of the byte 1, i.e. bits 8 .. 11. If counterOffset is not present the value is defined by the selected profile.

        Returns:
        The value or null

The offset shall be a multiplicity of 4 and it should be 0 whenever possible. For example, offset 8 means that the CRC will take the byte 1, i.e. bits 8..15.       • getDataIds

        long[] getDataIds()
        Get the values of the attribute DataId.

        This represents a unique numerical identifier. Note: ID is used for protection against masquerading. The details concerning the maximum number of values (this information is specific for each E2E profile) applicable for this attribute are controlled by a semantic constraint that depends on the category of the EndToEndProtection.

        Returns:
        The values (not null)

      • getDataIdMode

        long getDataIdMode()
        Query the value of the attribute DataIdMode.

        There are three inclusion modes how the implicit two-byte Data ID is included in the one-byte CRC: dataIDMode = 0: Two bytes are included in the CRC (double ID configuration) This is used in variant 1A. dataIDMode = 1: One of the two bytes byte is included, alternating high and low byte, depending on parity of the counter (alternating ID configuration). For even counter low byte is included; For odd counters the high byte is included. This is used in variant 1B. dataIDMode = 2: Only low byte is included, high byte is never used. This is applicable if the IDs in a particular system are 8 bits.

        Returns:
        The value or null

      • getMaxDeltaCounterInit

        long getMaxDeltaCounterInit()
        Query the value of the attribute MaxDeltaCounterInit.

        Initial maximum allowed gap between two counter values of two consecutively received valid Data, i.e. how many subsequent lost data is accepted. For example, if the receiver gets Data with counter 1 and MaxDeltaCounterInit is 1, then at the next reception the receiver can accept Counters with values 2 and 3, but not 4. Note that if the receiver does not receive new Data at a consecutive read, then the receiver increments the tolerance by 1.

        Returns:
        The value or null
